<h1>@HI{{ga}} (particle)</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{ha}} ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> is used with verbs such as @HI{{aru}}, @HI{{iru}}, @HI{{gozaimasu}} and @HI{{irassharu}}.
If a contrast is being presented then @HI{{ha}} can replaced <strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong>. Additionally, @HI{{ha}} is used 
if information is being presented about a subject that has already been identified.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of the predicate.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of an intransitive verb.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of the sentence when new, previously unknown, information is presented.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> is used with interrogative words in questions, both in general questions and when asking for
a choice.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a <a href="grammar-relative-clause.html">relative clause</a>. Note
that @HI{{no}} can often perform this function too.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a clause ending in @HI{{ka}}.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a subordinate or conditional clause when it differs from the
subject of the main clause.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of ability, such as @HI{{dekiru}} and @HI{{wakaru}}, and of the
<a href="grammar-verb-use-of-potential.html">potential</a> form of verbs.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of sensation, such as @HI{{mieru}} and @HI{{kikoeru}} as well as
@HI{{suru}} in some cases.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of necessity.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object ofadjectives of desire
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs and adjectives of emotion.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of ability.
</p>


<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{asoko ni @KJ{{private}}no@KT{{bo-rupenn}}<strong>ga</strong>arimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that my ballpoint pen over there?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
